        "created_at": "2025-04-05T08:04:13.557Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Since nougat, Android has used file based encryption to protect user data stored locally. Thatâ€™s been improved over the years, but according to developer docs, thereâ€™s still 2 main ways for apps to store data: credential encrypted storage, and device encrypted storage. Credential encrypted storage needs the user to enter their PIN or passcode before itâ€™s able to be used, but device encrypted. Storage works after boot but before first unlock (bfu). This is intended for things like alarm apps and incoming phone calls, since before, with full disc encryption, the phone was basically a brick until the passcode was entered.</p>\n<p>Signal has the ability to schedule messages to send in the future, and that apparently triggers the alarm API.</p>\n<p>Does signal use device encrypted storage or does it entirely remain within credential encrypted storage? How does signal behave if there are pending scheduled messages and the device reboots?</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 4,
        "updated_at": "2025-04-05T08:10:51.720Z",
